The word ‘Spirit’ in this context has no particular religious connotation. You could substitute the word ‘Heart’ or ‘Soul’ if you like. The essence of the phrase is simply that the best part of me wishes you well – in every way. In seeking to offer you delicious gluten and allergen-free foods, we nourish the body. description.text:
Bienvenido al segundo módulo de prácticas! Si estás leyendo esto damos por hecho que te has familiarizado con los conceptos de altura de capa, botton/top thickness, fil density y print speed, de no ser así te recomendamos que des una ojeada al módulo anterior donde hemos explicado estos conceptos y como se puede trabajar con ellos. Practica 4: Estructuras de apoyo/soporte Archivo a imprimir: Puente test Parámetros cura: Altura de capa: 0.20mm Bottom/Top thickness (mm): 0.8mm Fil density: 40% Print speed (mm/s): 40mm/s Tª extrusor: 190º PLA /210º ABS (esta temperatura es orientativa, seguir instrucciones del fabricante de filamento) Tº cama caliente: 60º PLA/ 100ª ABS (rociar previamente la superficie de impresión con un poco de laca para imprimir, sirve también la laca de la marca comercial Nely) Support:
Support type: La práctica de hoy se centra en este parámetro, ofrece dos opciones, en un desplegable, touching buildplate y everywhere. Estas opciones hacen más sencillas algunas impresiones para las que deberemos tener ya bastante práctica para que salgan bien, se trata de aquellas donde existe una estructura en voladizo, es decir, que no queda adherida a la base de impresión. Cuando un diseño presenta estas estructuras en el aire, dependiendo del punto en el que se encuentren en el diseño deberemos aplicar estas estructuras de apoyo, lo mismo pasa con los salientes en una figura. De no hacerlo se producirán lo que se llama caídas de capa, afectando a la estética y a la integridad de la pieza. Las estructuras que se generan se pueden extraer de la pieza impresa una vez acabada, en el proceso de post-impresión, con unos alicates pequeños o un cutter, siempre utilizándolo con precaución de no hacernos daño ni romper la pieza.
Para esta impresión elegiremos la primera de las dos opciones, touching buildplate, esta estructura se genera entre la plataforma de impresión y el punto donde existe riesgo de impresión. La otra opción, everywhere, genera estructuras a partir de cualquier punto que sea necesario. Platform adhesion type: None Para este parámetro no haremos práctica pero si explicaremos su función. Sirve para aquellas figuras que tienen poca superficie de contacto con la plataforma de impresión, al tener poco contacto es habitual que durante la impresión las piezas se despeguen y terminen dando vueltas sin control por la plataforma. Las dos opciones de este desplegable generan una estructura para conseguir más estructura, brim y raft, la primera genera una estructura más fina y la segunda una mayor estructura. Support type: None
Platform adhesion type: None Filament :1.75mm o 3mm depende del diámetro de filamento que utiliza tu impresora. Flow: 100% Ventilador de capa:Para activar el ventilador de capa tenemos que irnos a la siguiente pestaña, la de Advanced, allí iremos hasta el parámetro de enable cooling fan, aquí deberemos activar el cuadrado y que aparezca el símbolo de confirmación. IMPORTANTE que nuestra impresora 3D tenga ventilador, sino pasar directamente a la siguiente práctica o empezar a pensar en añadir este accesorio. Lo que nos permite es impedir las caídas de capa, es decir, que cuando imprimimos estructuras que no tienen una base de sustentación, que están en el aire, al no enfriarse lo suficientemente rápido, el plástico cae haciendo unos pequeños surcos y esto hace que la pieza pierda calidad y estética. La práctica consiste en imprimir la pieza de los puentes con y sin activar el ventilador y apreciar las diferencias, una vez tengamos las dos piezas, hacer una tercera impresión rebajando un poco la temperatura y volver a imprimir, si todo sale como debería ser, las piezas aumentaran de calidad.

author: Tangencial

description.text:
Here are the design files for a simple flexbox photobooth box and a podest for the button.
I used canon 500D as the camera, it sits on a platform inside, secured with a tripod screw that I think I printed off of thingiverse. I incorporated a cut up floodlight for the flashlight. I basically cut off the rear side of the cheapest floodlight with a dremel to make a hole for the 500D built in flash to shine through. The cutouts on the front side have sandpaper matte acrylic, edge lit by LEDs. All the thing is controlled with an arduino mini pro chinese clone put on a breadbord just controlling a few fets to turn on or off the various countdown or smile LEDs as well as to trigger the camera via the remote 2.5mm jack. I disassembled a chinese canon battery to fit inside a adjustable dc regulator, thus eliminating the need to change or charge the battery for the camera. There's a switch on the side with two RCA connectors for both the button podest as well as the dc power in. Note that these files are laid out on sheets for 100w 600x900mm co2 laser cutter.
I used both 4mm as well as 6mm MDF as the materials. Please check which files are for which thicknesses. Although I nailed everything basically with the first try there were some small problems with the files, so be diligent and check everything before cutting. This project was a quick less than 24 hour build, so take these files as-is with no guarantees. Almost forgot to mention- a lot of hot glue necessary.

Práctica 6: Retracciones Archivo a imprimir: Aniversary Roses Parámetros cura: Altura de capa: 0.20mm Bottom/Top thickness (mm): 0.8mm Fil density: 40% Print speed (mm/s): 40mm/s Tª extrusor: 190º PLA /210º ABS (esta temperatura es orientativa, seguir instrucciones del fabricante de filamento) Tº cama caliente: 60º PLA/ 100ª ABS (rociar previamente la superficie de impresión con un poco de laca para imprimir, sirve también la laca de la marca comercial Nely) Support:
Support type: None
Platform adhesion type: None Filament :1.75mm o 3mm depende del diametro de filamento que utiliza tu impresora. Flow: 100% Enable fan layer: Activado Retraction:
Speed: 40mm/s es la velocidad a la que el filamento será retraido, esta bien fijada si es elevada pero puede dar problemas si se aumenta demasiado, es positivo moverse en unos parametros similares a 40mm/s pero se puede ajustar.
Distance: se mide en mm, 0 supondrá mantener la retracción desactivada y a partir de aquí se marca la cantidad de filamento que retraerá la impresora. Esto significa que, al estar imprimiendo y cambiar de punto donde está extruyendo plástico, nuestra máquina recogerá un poco el filamento en sentido contrario a la extrusión. La retracción facilita que no aparezcan unos pequeños pelos en nuestras impresiones, la presencia de estos finos hilos nos indica que deberemos aumentar ligeramente la retracción pero con precaución ya que si nos pasamos, al volver a imprimir en el siguiente punto después de hacer el travel, nuestra máquina no extruirá el suficiente filamento. La práctica de hoy consiste en imprimir la rosa de aniversario poniendo la retracción a 0 y después modificando hasta 4.5mm por ejemplo y observar los resultados.

description.text:
This is take 2 of a laser alignment tool.  This tool, as the last one, mounts to the front of the nozzle of the Lasersaur laser tube.  It uses a simple  Quartet brand laser pointer from Petco and some cut to size mirrored plastic from AutoZone.  you get something like a 10"x10" sheet for $9.  You will need to cut the mirror and double side tape it in place.
You may have to use a little masking tape to shim up the fingers and get the device to stay in place on the nozzle due to print and nozzle tolerances.  Once you have the fit correct, simply slide the laser pointer into the barrel until the button stays depressed.  Place the device onto the laser nozzle and with the laser light on, simply rotate the tool to make sure that the beam line (it is a line not a point) rotates around its center and doesn't trace out a circle.  If it does trace out a circle, you can use another piece of double side tape on one end of the mirror to shim it and pint the laser parallel to the tube axis.  Keep shimming until the device stops tracing out a circle and the laser line spins in place.  
From there you can simply align each of the Lasersaur's mirrors.  This will get you "most" of the way and will make laser alignment a little easier.  I say most of the way, because there is an assumption that the CO2 laser beam is coaxial to the center axis of the nozzle, which is probably not exactly true.  Also due to the linearity of the laser pointer there is some error in finding it's center as well.  BUT this will get you most of the way there.
I have done some research and due to the way these low cost diodes are manufactured, the process will always give you a laser line vs a single point.  If you want a single point you need a tube style laser or pay a large amount for a more precise diode.  I figure...it's close enough for what we are trying to accomplish.
Good Luck!

This is a highly impractical .22 Long Rifle ammo box. It holds 413 rounds, 59 rounds per tray. Non-printed parts include:
  • Outer brass tube, 3.25" OD with a 1/16" wall, cut to 8.481".
  • Threaded rod, 10-24, about 10" long

    • Press two magnets in to the slots on the bottom of both the "Shelf" and "Bullet Tray". BE SURE TO PAY ATTENTION TO THE MAGNET ORIENTATION! Once you press them in, they are nearly impossible to get back out! Glue a disk magnet in the recesses on the top of "Outer Dome" and "Inner Dome", again, paying attention to the magnet orientation. The two domes should snap together and rotate freely. Glue the "Inner Dome" to the top of "Shelf - Top". Press one of the nuts in the bottom of "Slug - mid", and thread the rod up thru the hole. Use the other nut to secure the rod in place. I used a dab of JB-Weld on the threads to ensure it wouldn't slip over time. Then, glue on "Slug - top" and "Slug - Bottom", sand, prime, and paint. Dry-fit the assembly on to the brass tube, and cut the threaded rod so it's slightly undercut from the bottom of the brass tube. Glue the slug to the brass tube (I used JB-Weld). The shelves should snap together without modification, and are held in place with super glue. Glue the shelf assembly to the "Bottom".

This project has 3D-printed Wall Posts and Pegs for creating a custom maze that can be used for robotic maze-solving (on the cheap). The walls and floor of the maze are cut from 4mm foam core board. The black lines are 1" black fabric tape that support the use of a line-following sensor or sensor array for movement and turning. The motivation was to provide an easily transportable maze to use in teaching robotics and Artificial Intelligence. The robot pictured in the video is an mBot by Makeblock and the maze is one of the projects in a short eBook I've written titled "A Gentle Introduction to Robotics". (link). The STL files and the 123D Design project are included for easier remixing. All parts were printed in ABS with a 15% in-fill at normal print quality on a Lulzbot 3D Mini using gcode generated by Cura. Note: Although you can use 3D printed pegs, using threaded, flat-headed machine screws and wide washers will be much more durable as the pegs themselves are only 4mm in diameter. The next version of this project will be crafted from MDF and will use metal pegs.

description.text: This ninja star was modeled on Autodesk Inventor Professional 2012 and printed on the Makerbot Thing-O-Matic using 3mm plastic filament. I created design because i wanted to make something that served a cool and interesting purpose. Rather than making a useless figurine, i decided to manufacture a functional ninja star. I started by making this design in Autodesk Inventor and used the chamfer tool to make the blades of the star, which were made very thin. The point of this was to test how thin the Makerbot Thing-o-Matic could print. As it turns out, the makerbot did not print very thin. Also, the thinnest layers were very weak. What I would do differently next time is not to make the blades as thin. I would keep them thicker to make it stronger. Also, I would make the fill 100% because the ninja star could be a little bit heavier.

Download the Ninja_Star_Finalmm.stl file and print using a Makerbot machine. Scale the product to the size you desire.

This modular robust aluminum cutting bed was one of my high school student's design to replace the expensive, cumbersome and fragile aluminum honeycomb.
The concept was to use strips of 6061-T6 aluminum that could be easily replaced and removed individually without the need to replace the entire honeycomb.  Our student designed two different 3D printed brackets that bolt to the standard extrusion with the standard T-nuts to give us a 1" spaced bed and for 1/4 of the bed a 1/2" spaced bed.  Obviously if you are cutting lots of small parts all the time this specific design may not work for you, but you could redesign the brackets for your own custom spacing.
The aluminum is 6061-T6    0.063" thick x 1.5" tall by 33.5" long.  We ordered 70 pieces of which 12 we cut in half for the smaller spacing area.  We still have a number of pieces left over for replacements.  The total cost was $203....which btw is about what I spent on one sheet of honeycomb.  You could bevel the top edges to reduce reflections, but to be honest it's been working great without that hassle.
The only commitment is in cutting down the adjustable bed support to lay these extrusions on the literal bottom of the laser bed.  There just isn't enough height to keep this module as it was and still have proper focal length.  We calculated the height of 1.5" for the aluminum to give us the proper height to cut 3mm-12mm thick material without moving the bed.  If you wanted to etch taller things you can replace the strips with shorter ones or you can simply remove a couple of strips for the cut you are working on and replace them when you are done.  I have actually found this ability very nice for etching odd shaped items.
enjoy!

This thing is a 1:100 scale model of the famous Bailey Bridge of World War 2.   It is designed to be as close as possible to the full scale version with compromises for printability and assembly at such a small scale.
This is a challenging thing to print.  A standard size nozzle (0.4mm or higher) will struggle with the detail as an extrusion width of .25mm is demanded by some of the pieces.  
As with a full scale Bailey Bridge this model can be assembled in a number of variants: Single-Single, Double-Single, Triple-Single, and Triple-Double where the first word describes the number of bridge panels and the second the number of levels of those panels.  
Two lengths of bridge are included as STL's with one being of two sections and the other being of three sections.  In the full scale world each section is 10 feet long so this represents spans of 20 and 30 feet.  These sections can be joined to create a bridge of any length.
Finally, the bridge can be printed and assembled with or without a foot path.  There is a road bed with shorter transoms that can be used with a foot path free bridge.
The STL's shown here are for the three section Double-Single bridge.   The other variants are provided as ZIP files.  The source Sketchup file is also included and has a mount that can be used to display a Double-Single or Triple-Double bridge.

Don't panic! The printed part will not come into contact with your food ;) Just print the mold once and 2 of the inlays. Then print 1 handle and 1 pin. Push the pin into one of the inlays and press the handle (bottom covered in superglue) onto the inlay. Put the other inlay into the mold (ribs facing up). Done. Now just use wrapping film on the mold, put your minced pork into the mold, cover with another wrapping film and press with the handle inlay part your pork. Done!!! Now you've got your McRib patty. Freeze them for 2-3 hours until they're solid. Now you can cook them in a pan for 2-3 minutes each side.   • Print "spiral christmas tree" and "spiral christmas tree star" with 20% infill and 0.8mm Shell thickness. (You may get some sag on the overhanging branches, but that makes this object look a little more like a tree.)

  • Print "spiral christmas tree garland" with 100% infill so it stays flexible but sturdy.

  • Print "spiral christmas tree trunk" and "spiral christmas tree post" with Cura's "Spiralize the outer contour" and "Only follow mesh surface" options, and an 0.8mm Shell thickness. (Although for the post, it may not matter.)

Insert the trunk into the bottom of the tree and the post into the top.
Bend the garland near the central circle.
Insert the tab of the garland into one of the slots on the bottom of the tree.
Arrange the garland around the outside of the tree, then twist the central circle until it looks as you like it. Place the central circle around the top post to hold it in place. (The central hole and post are both 5-sided, so it should stay in place.)
Place the star on top of the post.
No glue should be necessary if you are placing this on a table top.

[Simple front and top cover for the Ultimaker 2 (standard or extended).]
I wanted to create a simple top and front cover to enclose my Ultimaker 2 Extended to maintain a higher ambient temperature inside the printer for ABS prints.
For the top cover, I decided to buy a Sterilite 16 Qt storage tote from Target (<$3) and design clips to secure the tote to the top of the printer. I punched two holes in the lip of the tote to accommodate the two screws towards the back of the top of the printer.
For the front cover, I ordered a piece of clear acrylic sheet, 12" x 24" x 0.236" that I cut the length down to 16-1/4". I considered printing one of the hinges shared here on YM, but I wanted a simpler solution that didn't leave gaps between the acrylic sheet and the printer's front face. My design uses two fixed lower clips and one removable upper clip.
